{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-blog-post-js","path":"/day-75/","result":{"data":{"site":{"siteMetadata":{"title":"zainsci-blog"}},"markdownRemark":{"id":"2297a932-61f4-563e-a1e2-319daceacfa5","excerpt":"As mentioned in the last post about threads, Multithreading is the ability of the CPU to run multiple threads of execution at the same time while sharingâ€¦","html":"<p>As mentioned in the last post about threads, Multithreading is the ability of the CPU to run multiple threads of execution at the same time while sharing resources of a single or multiple cores. Threads are of mainly two levels, user threads and kernel threads.</p>\n<p>User threads are supported above the kernel and are managed without the help from the kernel and kernel threads are directly supported by the Operating System. A relationship must exist between user threads and kernel threads. There are maily three types of realtions used in user-kernel threading model. These are following.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Many-to-One Model</li>\n<li>One-to-One Model</li>\n<li>Many-to-Many Model</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Many-to-One Model</h3>\n<p>Many-to-One model maps many user-level threads to a single kernel-level threads. It is done in the user space by the thread library. In Many-to-One model if a thread makes a system blocking call it will block entire process. Only one thread can access the kernel at a time which makes it unable for multi threads to run in parallel on multiprocessors.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 630px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/blog/static/c312f4fdce8c584f5ce74caa922c0840/07635/many-to-one.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 45.56962025316456%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Many To One Multi-threading Model\"\n        title=\"Many To One Multi-threading Model\"\n        src=\"/blog/static/c312f4fdce8c584f5ce74caa922c0840/828fb/many-to-one.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/blog/static/c312f4fdce8c584f5ce74caa922c0840/ff44c/many-to-one.jpg 158w,\n/blog/static/c312f4fdce8c584f5ce74caa922c0840/a6688/many-to-one.jpg 315w,\n/blog/static/c312f4fdce8c584f5ce74caa922c0840/828fb/many-to-one.jpg 630w,\n/blog/static/c312f4fdce8c584f5ce74caa922c0840/0ede0/many-to-one.jpg 945w,\n/blog/static/c312f4fdce8c584f5ce74caa922c0840/07635/many-to-one.jpg 952w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 630px) 100vw, 630px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<h3>One-to-One Model</h3>\n<p>One-to-One model maps each user thread to a single kernel thread. This way other threads can keep runnig while one thread is asking for a blocking system call. It also allows multiple threads to run in parallel on multiprocessors.</p>\n<p>The drawback to this model is that running one user thread requires one kernel thread to run with it which can cause a burden on the system.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 630px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/blog/static/9c45c9c979992c538654d4f6ef72172e/0ede0/one-to-one.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 45.56962025316456%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"One To One Multi-threading Model\"\n        title=\"One To One Multi-threading Model\"\n        src=\"/blog/static/9c45c9c979992c538654d4f6ef72172e/828fb/one-to-one.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/blog/static/9c45c9c979992c538654d4f6ef72172e/ff44c/one-to-one.jpg 158w,\n/blog/static/9c45c9c979992c538654d4f6ef72172e/a6688/one-to-one.jpg 315w,\n/blog/static/9c45c9c979992c538654d4f6ef72172e/828fb/one-to-one.jpg 630w,\n/blog/static/9c45c9c979992c538654d4f6ef72172e/0ede0/one-to-one.jpg 945w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 630px) 100vw, 630px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<h3>Many-to-Many Model</h3>\n<p>Many-to-Many model maps many user-level threads to less or equal number of kernle threads.The number of threads may be specific to an application or to a particular machine.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 630px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/blog/static/8a9932ec2512fafe870c49acd475a10d/30cf6/many-to-many.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 44.93670886075949%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Many To Many Multi-threading Model\"\n        title=\"Many To Many Multi-threading Model\"\n        src=\"/blog/static/8a9932ec2512fafe870c49acd475a10d/828fb/many-to-many.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/blog/static/8a9932ec2512fafe870c49acd475a10d/ff44c/many-to-many.jpg 158w,\n/blog/static/8a9932ec2512fafe870c49acd475a10d/a6688/many-to-many.jpg 315w,\n/blog/static/8a9932ec2512fafe870c49acd475a10d/828fb/many-to-many.jpg 630w,\n/blog/static/8a9932ec2512fafe870c49acd475a10d/0ede0/many-to-many.jpg 945w,\n/blog/static/8a9932ec2512fafe870c49acd475a10d/30cf6/many-to-many.jpg 956w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 630px) 100vw, 630px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>","frontmatter":{"title":"Day 75 - Multithreading Models","date":"March 16, 2021","description":null,"tags":["Operating-Systems"]}},"previous":{"fields":{"slug":"/day-74/"},"frontmatter":{"title":"Day 74 - Threads"}},"next":{"fields":{"slug":"/day-76/"},"frontmatter":{"title":"Day76 - Threading Libraries And Examples"}}},"pageContext":{"id":"2297a932-61f4-563e-a1e2-319daceacfa5","previousPostId":"e3387b78-59f2-503c-8858-4d0b4e179107","nextPostId":"aefc5faf-1f21-5146-8edf-0604850a1be6"}},"staticQueryHashes":["1578995489","290055352","3347749741","3894407297"]}